An ionic bond is formed by the electrostatic attraction between positive and negative 
ions. The bond forms between two atoms when one or more electrons are transferred from the valence shell of one atom to the valence shell of the other. The atom that loses electrons becomes a cation (positive ion), and the atom that gains electrons becomes an anion (negative ion). Any given ion tends to attract as many neighboring ions of 
opposite charge as possible.

